TITLE: Paraguard - Copper IUD Experiences?
BODY: I ve had the copper IUD for around 5 months and I love it! For me, I ve always used ''lite'' tampons simply because it is more comfortable and I have a small vagina. When I got the IUD inserted it honestly was the worst pain I have experienced - I wanted to just tell them to stop (at the time I was 26 and I have had no prior pregnancies). I am so glad that I went through with it. I ve read about all the bad things that can happen with copper IUDs (i.e. terrible cramps, heavy periods). Myself, I have experienced slightly heavier periods however it is more that I spot a few days prior to bleeding. Nothing major it s just an annoyance. Also my periods last a day or two longer however they are still as light as they have been. Cramps are the worst part. I ve always had bad cramps and am prescribed vicodin in order to endure them. Sometimes between periods (usually during ovulation according to my phone app) cramps are unbearable. I ve always had terrible cramps though. They are even worse since getting the IUD however for me, it has been totally worth it. /n/nWhen I first got it I was cramping for a good while and bled for the two weeks prior to my period before things became ''normalized.'' Honestly there are parts about the copper IUD that I think suck (mainly the intense cramps between periods) but I will never suggest that anyone not do it. It is seriously amazing and for me, the cons are very, very slight when thinking of the benefits.

TITLE: Pit Bull Training Question?
BODY: This question is for responsible Pit owners and/or trainers:  In addition to our 8 other dogs, we were ''blessed'' recently with a pit or pit-mix puppy.  We've fostered a lot of dogs, but we've tried to stay away from breeds that might not work well in our pack setting and/or farm animals. But what do you do? The rescues are FULL of casually-bred pit puppies.  We've tried to rehome him, but I honestly didn't completely trust the 2 people who applied for him, so it was either keep him ourselves & continue to try to place him or have him euthanized (he's only 6 weeks old.)   He's smart, strong-willled, loving, & everything you normally associate with this breed. He picked up ''sit'' after about 4 times, and we're teaching him what are his ''chew toys'' and what's NOT a chew-toy,  and that humans get to eat first, etc. My question, though, is about play-fighting. You can't do much about genetics, but we don't want to encourage any dog-aggression. He and our other younger dogs tussle as all puppies will (we have a young Dane female who's already 90 lbs. & also a scrappy little red heeler mix.)  Puppies are going to play, but should I curb rough-housing at some point? Is it good that he's ''fighting'' at a young age with dogs that can put his chubby little self on the ground, or will this just encourage him to want to fight even harder?  Again, I'm not taking owning this dog lightly, and I want to do everything I can to encourage his success in our household or in his future forever-home.

If there is some sort of distraction, my mind wonders toward it, and i find it challenging to ignore it when others easily do. I've even gotten comments on how I'm 'slower' than the rest of my group.
